**End of Week Report - August 9, 2019**

**Project Name: Novare Internal**

Discussed the Data Science team KPIs and had a one on one meeting with each member. The goal is to fix all of their individual development plans and interact with them amidst a very busy day and to set SMART goals

Already discussed with the team what are the next steps and also asked them to start working on the discussed internal data science projects

**Project Name: Chinabank Analytics**

We have a new engagement on Chinabank, almost the same as the previous engagement though this time we are more detailed on the project scope. We still lack 1 sign to proceed with the project, however the 2 other signees, as mentioned to me, will persuade the other signee therefore let‚Äôs prepare for this engagement as well. Right now, I am seeing Jeff and Adrian to do the chinabank project

**Project Name: SMART ETL POC**

I was on-boarded on the SMART Talend POC, with the goal of leading the team and making sure that every client expectations were met during this POC. We are very pressed on time,  therefore there is a need for us to work on holidays, but that will depend on the daily team achievements

There is a really high chance that we might get this project with SMART, since even if the business is leaning more towards another party and sometimes impeding our progress by not providing any needed documents, as of the moment we do not have any blockers to finish the POC. Also I have informed Julie and Elton already that on the project proper, we can‚Äôt afford not to have the OEM parser for nokia CDRs

I am also helping on other scripts since some of the scripts are written in scala. There are some instances that we need to call OS level scripts from talend. 

Presentation for use case A and F will be on August 15, 2019. Shashank will need our help since some of the components for these use cases are tied up with use case B which the team is currently doing. Everything is on schedule so far

Checked some discrepancies on the SMS CDR. This is due to some errors made on the mapping by Mark Tan before he left. It was quickly fixed as to not affect on any ingestion workflow

The target is to finish the whole dev work on use case B this week (August 9, 2019) to make room for bulk tests and optimizations. I will push Mark to finish CM CDR today. We actually need more time however Alex needs something to be presented by August 15 (2 use cases out of 3) because as mentioned by vivian, Alex is pro Talend and would like to award this already and start with project proper preparations and discussions. 

Will work on some reports needed for other use cases (like the geo spatial report). Any requirement which is do not have any Talend native component are written on scripts then will be called by Talend on OS level

**Project Name: Aboitiz Power Data Lake**

There was a discussion with the contract and other changes. AEV procurement called me and was so irritated because to them, MDI-Novare does not have strong collaboration and relationship with Talend. They gave us 1 month to answer and review everything and yet they mentioned that no reply was sent to them. However, everything was quickly fixed and arranged this week as to not impede the project proper any further. There will be SRS and Architecture review on August 20, 2019 (date subject to change)

GE and OSI PI APIs were discussed this week. These are the remaining data sources which were not yet discussed to us, thus completing the Client KT to Vendor phase of the data discovery. Mark already sent the unfinished mapping documents to Jas. 

**Project Name: Globe EDA**

Discussed with Reinald the key concepts of machine learning and how to make some business out of it. Explained to him the activities a normal EDA usually have and helped him with his clarifications, question sending, and EE creation. Globe will answer all the questions sent, and actually also asking us to recommend something which we think they need.

### This exercise involves building a non-trivial dictionary.
### The subject is books.

### The key for each book is its title
### The value associated with that key is a dictionary

### ### In that dictionary there will be Three keys: They are all strings, they are:
### ### "Pages", "Author", "Publisher"

### ### ### "Pages" is associated with one value - an int

### ### ### "Author is associated with a dictionary as value
### ### ### ### That "Author" dictionary has two keys: "First", and "Last" each with a string value

### ### ### "Publisher" is associated with a dictionary as value
### ### ### ### That "Publisher" dict has one key "Location" with a string as value.

### An Example might look like:
### {"Harry Potter": {"Pages":200, "Author":{"First":"J.K", "Last":"Rowling"}, "Publisher":{"Location":"NYC"}},
###  "Fear and Lothing in Las Vegas": { ...}}

### Code a function called "build_book_dict"
### ACCEPT five inputs, all lists of n-length
### ### A list of titles, pages, first<name>, last<name>, and <publisher>location.

### RETURN a dictionary as described above.
### Keys must be spelled just as they appear above - correctly and capitalized.

### YOUR ANSWER BELOW

def build_book_dict(titles, pages, firsts, lasts, locations):
    """
    Return a nested dictionary storing information about Books
    
    Positional Arguments:
        titles -- A list of strings
        pages -- A list of ints
        firsts -- A list of strings
        lasts -- A list of strings
        locations -- A list of strings
    
    Example:
        titles = ["Harry Potter", "Fear and Lothing in Las Vegas"]
        pages = [200, 350]
        firsts = ["J.K.", "Hunter"]
        lasts = ["Rowling", "Thompson"]
        locations = ["NYC", "Aspen"]
        
        book_dict = build_book_dict(titles, pages, firsts, lasts, locations)
        print(book_dict) # -->
            {'Fear and Lothing in Las Vegas': {'Publisher': {'Location': 'Aspen'},
            'Author': {'Last': 'Thompson', 'First': 'Hunter'}, 'Pages': 350},
            'Harry Potter': {'Publisher': {'Location': 'NYC'},
            'Author': {'Last': 'Rowling', 'First': 'J.K.'}, 'Pages': 200}}
        
    """

    
    return dict()

# üí° Using Cloud Custodian for Policy Enforcement

Automating policies in cloud environments are a common concern for companies, and including our own environment since it's easy to lose track of resources and compliance.

AWS has rules engines like AWS Config, but that costs money as your infrastructure gets bigger.

**Cloud Custodian** looks like it's capable of doing the same thing, if not more and with actual actions (i.e., stop noncompliant resources after X days) when rules are broken.

- Home - https://cloudcustodian.io/
- [Policy Examples](https://cloudcustodian.io/docs/aws/examples/index.html)
- [Example: Tag Compliance with Termination for Non-compliant Resources](https://cloudcustodian.io/docs/aws/examples/tagcompliance.html)

# üí° Exploration on ECS, EKS and Fargate

Keifer Fababeir, Joseph Ongsingco, Kent Flores and I just attended AWS' seminar on this, so I'm sharing the three Labs demos that they encouraged users to follow so they'll learn.

We can apply this to get used to EKS and ECS. I have some ideas on my mind already on what we'll do with Armory.

- [**Break a Monolith Application into Microservices**][1] - The easy course to using ECS.
- [**CatsNDogs Workshop**][2] - A more advanced course to learning ECS. It's a self-paced course that tackles production concerns.
- [**EKS Workshop**][3] - The longest, but still self-paced course featuring Kubernetes. Contains interesting topics that you'd want for a fully-functional K8S setup.

## Why bother ECS?

I can see a real incentive to use ECS and changing between Fargate and EC2 styles, versus Kubernetes. It's all worth noting imo.

[1]: https://aws.amazon.com/getting-started/projects/break-monolith-app-microservices-ecs-docker-ec2/
[2]: https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-ecs-catsndogs-workshop
[3]: https://eksworkshop.com/

# ‚ÑπÔ∏è Sharing: Including Documents in Version Control

I've been trying out lately how we can improve software projects by checking in documentation along with our source code, and so far [`mkdocs`](https://www.mkdocs.org/) is pretty nice for its simplicity.

*Here's a video demo of Armory's documentation with just a few minutes of mkdocs. The existing docs that I wrote only took little to no editing and it worked. I just had to reorganize things.*

How it works:
- Just write Markdown files in a `docs` folder.
- Provide a simple `mkdocs.yml` file
- Install `mkdocs` (super-easy: just `pip install mkdocs`) then use it to `mkdocs serve`
- You have a fully-functional static site for documentation.

I want to push this into a *standard* somehow, since having your docs as part of your code has a lot of benefits:

- It's readable anywhere; just open it on your favorite Markdown editor.
- It's *resilient*. Other docs either rely on the cloud (Google Docs) or is difficult to update or find because of discoverability issues. Putting your work in the same repo makes that a no-brainer.
- It gets git powers as well -- docs are version-controlled according to their current version, can be `diff`ed, and no need to keep a "version history" session since git's commit system makes that mandatory.
- It's highly portable. You can convert this to any format, from PDFs, to DOCX, to HTML.
- It's easily hostable. This is as easy as taking an Angular site to production -- just place it in an S3 bucket and it's immediately viewable.

# ‚ÑπÔ∏è SEG Documents

Just an FYI, we've had various documents that are handy to keep in mind in day-to-day work.

- I'm maintaining a [**For New Employees**][3] guide in Armory. This has been updated quite a bit since the last time.

-  John Gregory Jose has shared and listed the essential [**SEG Documents**][2] in this Google Drive. 

- Aiza Bermudez is also maintaining a [**Roll-in Checklist here**][1]. (Very good stuff, I'll try to consolidate those items with what I've made.)

Greg, Aiza, thanks for the good work on the above!

If anyone has more documents or templates to share, please feel free to contribute! Building our knowledge base is key to enjoying a seamless process in the future.

The Vicious Circle

Three sisters from a poor family petitioned the abbot of the Laughing Monkey Clan for admission to the Temple as developers.

‚ÄúI cannot hire any of you,‚Äù said the abbot after he looked at their r√©sum√©s and code samples. ‚ÄúYou do not have the necessary experience.‚Äù

‚ÄúBut it is the same complaint everywhere we go!‚Äù protested one of the sisters. ‚ÄúHow are we to acquire experience if we are refused entrance to every place that offers experience simply because we lack experience?‚Äù

Master Kaimu happened to be passing by and overheard this. He said to the girls: ‚ÄúDesire is the root of all suffering. If you cannot do what you desire, then do what you must, so that in your spare time you may do what you truly love.‚Äù

The master then departed, but the girls were not comforted.

- - -
Several months later the master came upon these same three sisters sharing a humble meal in the village. He asked them how they fared.

The first said, ‚ÄúBy day I do carpentry to pay the bills, and by night I carve sculptures for my amusement.‚Äù

The second said, ‚ÄúBy day I sell fish to pay the bills, and by night I practice dance for my amusement.‚Äù

The third said, ‚ÄúBy day I repair garments to pay the bills, and by night I code little applications for my amusement.‚Äù

Kaimu returned to the abbot and, telling him what had transpired, said, ‚ÄúAdmit the third sister to your clan, for she has what we seek.‚Äù

The abbot asked, ‚ÄúShould we not advise her elder sisters to follow her example, that they might gain experience and also be admitted?‚Äù

‚ÄúNull,‚Äù said Kaimu. ‚ÄúHow can we advise them on ‚Äòwhat to truly love?‚Äò‚Äù

# ‚Ñπ Amazon Partner Network ‚Ä¢ Register APN Accounts!

Hello everyone! We'd like to remind everyone that we're partnered with Amazon, and with it comes along the facilities for the Amazon Partner Network (APN).

# **[Please take the time to register here][2], and read on.**

## What's this all about?

Using your MDI/Novare addresses, you can register in the APN and take some of the courses that are available there. Part of the benefits include access to some of the virtual (online/on-demand) courses available at no-cost, and it's a good place to begin between the actual certification exams.

If you're ever idle at work, studying AWS is a good use of time. Completing courses and certifications will lead you to being better equipped at work and earning good results for your performance appraisal.

- [Read more about the APN here][1].

- [**Check the AWS Partner Learning Path Tool**][3] so you can see what courses you'll want to take.

**The link to always remember is [aws.training](https://www.aws.training).**

## Any Recommendations?

Personally, I would recommend this route:

- Take the [**AWS Technical Professional**][6] course. It's online and I recommend taking it if you have the free time to do so.

- Take the time to actually use AWS! The [Free Tier][7] is readily available and I recommend registering for your own account to learn how it works. (Tip: You can pay for AWS using GCash or PayMaya, and you can keep costs low by utilizing it only when needed and setting an AWS Budget)

- Aim for[ **Associate-level certification!**][8] It's a main part of the [Developer][4] and [Architect][5] learning paths. Talk to your admin TMs to learn more on this, since training courses can be routed through our APN membership.

[1]: https://aws.amazon.com/partners/apn-portal/ "Learn more about the APN Portal"
[2]: https://partnercentral.awspartner.com/selfregisterpartner "Self-registration for Amazon Partner Central"
[3]: https://pages.awscloud.com/AWS-Partner-Learning-Path-Tool.html "AWS Partner Learning Path Tool"
[4]: https://aws.amazon.com/training/path-developing/ "Developer Learning Path"
[5]: https://aws.amazon.com/training/path-architecting/ "Architect Learning Path"
[6]: https://www.aws.training/learningobject/curriculum?id=11276 "AWS Technical Professional (Digital) - Curriculum"
[7]: https://aws.amazon.com/free/ "AWS Free Tier"
[8]: https://aws.amazon.com/certification/certification-prep/ "AWS Certification Prep"

Kubernetes has always been positioned for stateless use cases. But, it seems the folks at Heptio (now VMware) are working on stuff that makes containers applicable for generic use cases.

Developer visibility of k8 deployments for app profiling with Octant. 
https://blogs.vmware.com/cloudnative/2019/08/12/octant-reveals-objects-running-in-kubernetes-clusters/

Persistent storage. 
https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/configure-pod-container/configure-persistent-volume-storage/

Monitoring via Operator. 
https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/extend-kubernetes/operator/
https://itnext.io/kubernetes-monitoring-with-prometheus-in-15-minutes-8e54d1de2e13

Backup and DR. 
https://github.com/heptio/velero

Security of Internet packages via Admission Control. 
https://github.com/open-policy-agent/gatekeeper (This was a key concern in both P11 and BDO where they want to use airgapped networks)

But is this the future of containers? It seems to be moving towards mirroring VM functionality.

**To: All Tenants of MDI Corporate Center (BGC-Taguig)**

With reference to the circular forwarded by the Bonifacio Global City Estate Association (BGCEA), please be informed that the **MDI Corporate Center WILL BE participating in the 2nd Quarter Nationwide Simultaneous Earthquake Drill (NSED)** by the National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council (NDRRMC) on the following schedule:

**Date: June 20, 2019 (Thursday)**
**Time: 2:00PM**

**What to expect BEFORE, DURING and AFTER the earthquake drill:**

**1.** At 2:00PM, BGCEA will trigger their alarm to signify the official start of the drill for all participating locations/buildings.

**2. **MDI Building Management Team will activate the General Alarm upon hearing the signal of BGCEA. 

**3. **All elevators will be turned off during the whole duration of the drill. Kindly inform your guests to come earlier if you have scheduled meetings at this time. 

**4. **Everybody is required to perform the DROP, COVER and HOLD procedure upon hearing the General Alarm. Floor Marshalls must direct their staff to use the nearest FIRE EXIT for proper evacuation. 

**5. **Please proceed to the evacuation area at the open lot located along 39th Street in front of the MDI Corporate Center Parking Entrance. 

**6. **Floor Marshalls must count the total number of participants and report to the Command Center for monitoring. 

**7. **Once BCGEA Marshall declares that the Drill is done, the Property Manager will announce via Megaphone that all tenants may now return to their work area. Elevators will be operational by then.

**Please treat this drill seriously for everybody's awareness, knowledge and safety.** We are looking forward to your cooperation and continuous support as we enhance our preparedness to any eventualities.

Thank you,
Facilities and Inventory Management

Warning! PLEASE READ. Especially golfers. 

1.) A doctor friend came to me to chat and said that the weather was very hot. Under the sun, it could reach 40 degrees C. He said...
> At 40 degrees, if you drink ice water in an instant, the micro blood vessels could explode. One of his friends just went into the house to wash his feet with cold water. Then his eyes could not see clearly, and he passed out. Only the ears could hear the sound. He was terrified!

2.) The temperature in some places has reached 38 degrees C or higher, but the temperature of the body sense should be higher. The danger is not just with drinking ice cold water. The same danger may occur with even washing hands / washing your face / washing your feet. You must not subject any part of the hot  body to temperature shock with cold water.  You need about 30 minutes to allow the body to cool down and adjusted to the indoor temperature. Drink natural temperature water / luke- warm water of  around 34 to 36 degrees C.

3.) There is a very strong man. The doctor had examined him in the hospital about three years ago. He met the man again and was surprised to find that he had a stroke. He was in a bad condition. The man told the doctor...
> Recently,  on a hot day, upon returning home,  in order to quickly cool off from the heat, I immediately took a cold shower. I felt that I could not move my jaws properly. I  immediately called an ambulance to send me to the hospital. That saved my life.

Remember, especially on a hot day, avoid fridge water or ice-cold water to cool off as it  will cause rapid contraction of blood vessels. 

Adults with young children at home should inform their helpers about this.

### The weather is abnormal recently.  It may be nice to have a cold drink to cool down,  but it is very dangerous! Avoid gulping down the drink, drink it  slowly.

Please pass this safety message to your family and friends. 

It may save a life!

Novare ID 2019

 

Join our first project as a community, our brand new Novare company ID!

But this time we are shaking things up with an ID that reflects the real YOU!

Take your own photo (waist up) and send up to three photos of yourself that you'd like to be your company ID Photo.

Some guidelines for the pics:

- Must be High resolution (at least 3MB)

- Nice contrast to the background (Preferably against white or one entire flat color, so it can be easily edited. As seen from the samples, try avoiding dark blue or grey, because you might blend in with the texture.)

- Comfortable front-facing (full face must be seen).

- Nothing covering the face or head (no shades, no hats/caps).

- No app stickers or heavy filters.

- No costumes, wigs or outrageous/scandalous apparel.

- Must be recent (within the past 3 months).

- Bawal gusgusin; bawal pambahay; no tattered clothing.

- No clothing with offensive statements.

- No 'revealing' clothing. No plunging necklines and unbuttoned shirts/blouses, spaghetti straps and tube tops.

- Do not submit altered photos (submit a photo of your most authentic self).

- Smiling is encouraged - positive or neutral disposition.

- No inappropriate poses and gang signs, please.

- You can use props that reflect who you are like gadgets, musical instruments, paint brushes, etc. Items that play up your personality and/or interest/s.

PS. This is for regular employees only

.

Submit your pics to our Senior Creative Designer, Ian Navarro ian.navarro@novare.com.hk by February 22, 2019!

Multi-cloud management has always been the holy grail of infrastructure management. You see many tools and vendors promise it. But to date, none do it well. You heard me right... NONE. 

Imagine being able to move a VM from on premise Openstack to AWS. All vendors promise they have products that can do it. But the moment you ask how are the IPs addresses, DNS entities and network/security policies moved? They start enumerating exceptions and roadmaps.

However, a full containerized approach has the potential to solve this problem. A policy and configuration that is declarative. Of course, only if the application is written properly to use containers. This is why this space should be keenly studied including tools like Istio.

DevSecOps: another buzzword to add to our vocabulary. This article describes 6 main stages in the cycle that strongly involve security. Do we have an appropriate security practice and tool for each? 

Code Analysis - SonarCube, Fortify, Linters,... 
Automated Testing - Junit, Mockito, Selenium, Robotium, The Monkey,... 
Change Management - Git, Redmine, Jira,... 
Compliance Monitoring - Appd, w4af,... 
Threat Investigation - ? 
Personnel Training -? 

Does Novare have a play?

We do take pride in being responsible for one of the largest Big Data deployments in the market at 45 petabytes in Globe. Yes, that is 45 and 15 zeros. (Half the alleged data storage capability of Cmdr. Data in Star Trek or 5% of all the words EVER spoken). We have also worked with other clients in the telecommunications space such as Smart and Robi. 

However,  we don't seem to be able to get good traction outside this area. Why? My guess is that unlike telcos most organizations do not have highly utilized analytics needs. They are most adhoc and it is only the storage that is committed. As we all know the economics of Hadoop on prem only make sense if utilization is high. 

An option is to make a hybrid and cloud play. What is Novare's hybrid play? 

Something to think about this morning.
